    "slug": "social-proof-landing",
    "lang": "en",
    "title": "Social Proof on Landing Pages: Real Examples Used by Service Businesses",
    "description": "Testimonials, numbers, and client logos — which ones actually increase trust and conversion on landing pages.",
    "date": "2026-06-22",
    "tags": [
      "conversion",
      "landing-page",
      "social-proof"
    ],
    "html": "<p>Many landing pages display testimonials, but not all of them create real impact. Some are too generic, some are too long, and some even make visitors more skeptical.</p>\n<p>Good social proof is not about having “many testimonials,” but about <strong>credibility</strong> and <strong>relevance</strong> to the person viewing the page.</p>\n<h2>Types of Social Proof That Work Best</h2>\n<h3>1. Testimonials with name + photo + specific results</h3>\n<p><strong>Weak:</strong> &gt; “The service was excellent.” — Anonymous</p>\n<p><strong>Stronger:</strong> &gt; “After 3 sessions, my acne reduced by 80%. I now feel much more confident during presentations.”   &gt; — Rina Wijaya, Marketing Manager, Jakarta</p>\n<h3>2. Specific numbers and statistics</h3>\n<p>Strong examples: - “Helped 2,400+ clients since 2021” - “Average reply time: 18 minutes” - “92% of clients continued to the next package”</p>\n<p>These numbers create a sense of safety because they are measurable.</p>\n<h3>3. Client logos or media coverage</h3>\n<p>If your business has been featured in the media or worked with recognizable clients, display their logos. This works especially well for B2B or professional services.</p>\n<h3>4. Short case studies (1 paragraph + results)</h3>\n<p>Instead of just testimonials, tell a short story: - The problem the client faced - The solution you provided - The result they achieved</p>\n<h2>Common Mistakes When Displaying Social Proof</h2>\n<ul><li>Testimonials that are too long (people rarely read them)</li><li>No photo or full name</li><li>Using testimonials from people who are not relevant to your target audience</li><li>Showing too many testimonials at once (overwhelming)</li></ul>\n<h2>Real Examples We Have Implemented</h2>\n<p><strong>Skin Clinic</strong> - Displayed 3 testimonials with photos + before/after results (not just text) - Added “Trusted by 1,800+ patients in Greater Jakarta”</p>\n<p><strong>Premium Residential Property</strong> - Showed logos of media that covered their projects - Displayed one short case study: “The Pratama family bought a 3BR unit after only 2 visits”</p>\n<p><strong>Education / Mentoring Program</strong> - Showed photos of participants + their current job titles - Added “87% of participants received a promotion within 6 months”</p>\n<h2>Social Proof Checklist</h2>\n<ul class=\"blog-checklist\"><li>Every testimonial includes a name + photo (or initials + city)</li><li>Results mentioned are specific (not just “good”)</li><li>No more than 4–5 testimonials on the main page</li><li>At least one supporting statistic or number</li><li>Social proof matches the audience visiting the page</li></ul>\n<h2>Next Step</h2>\n<p>If you want to strengthen the social proof on your landing page, we can help with:</p>\n<ul><li>Auditing your existing testimonials</li><li>Rewriting testimonials to be stronger and more credible</li><li>Creating short case study templates</li></ul>\n<p><a href=\"/kontak\">Start a conversation via WhatsApp</a> or explore our work on the <a href=\"/layanan\">Services</a> and <a href=\"/portfolio\">Portfolio</a> pages.</p>\n<p>This article is based on social proof patterns we have applied across more than 20 landing page projects for service businesses.</p>",
